<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO ONE HAS FAINTEST IDEA WHAT TO DO; 
</P>
<P>
SOCIAL PROBLEMS: THE REPUBLICANS LACK THE WILL TO SOLVE THEM, BUT DEMOCRATS 
LACK THE WAY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES KRAUTHAMMER, Charles Krauthammer writes a syndicated column in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
We are living in a time of unprecedented national consensus. The great 
ideological arguments of the past -- over Russia, Vietnam, Nicaragua, the 
welfare state, nuclear deterrence, etc. 
</P>
<P>
-- are over. There are only two real issues on the American agenda. Debt: the 
budget deficit and associated debt problems (e.g., the S&amp;L debacle). And 
race: namely, the social problems (drugs, violence, poor schooling, family 
break-up) of the urban underclass. 
</P>
<P>
On debt, everybody knows what has to be done -- raise taxes and/or cut 
entitlements -- but no one of either party has the courage to do it. On race, 
the opposite is true: Everyone wants to do something but no one has the 
faintest idea what to do. When the two great issues of the day are in a state 
of paralysis, one for lack of will and one for lack of way, it is not 
surprising that both government and opposition appear marginal. 
</P>
<P>
In an era of ideological consensus, the parties naturally find themselves 
engaged in narrow arguments over means. Everybody is for education, child care 
and clean air. In the clean-air bill now being hammered out in Congress, the 
fight is about a little less tailpipe emissions here, a little more high-sulfur 
coal there. Important issues, but hardly galvanizing. 
</P>
<P>
Which explains the attraction of would-be Democratic issues such as 
protectionism, Social Security and demobilization. They all have the potential 
to galvanize. It is therefore a critique of sorts to say that the Democrats as 
a party are not hungry, not ruthless, not irresponsible enough to seize these 
issues as a route to power. 
</P>
<P>
But let's not confuse partisanship with statesmanship. Populism is fun and it 
may be profitable. But it isn't vision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
