<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NATIONWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
WINTER ENCORES IN PLAINS, EAST COAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An early spring storm whipped up winter-like conditions from the plains to the 
East Coast, and record low temperatures extended from Alabama to Kansas. Snow 
was reported over Michigan and in the East from Cape Cod to North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
Up to 10 inches fell in parts of West Virginia, making driving hazardous. Three 
inches fell in Philadelphia, southern New Jersey and Ohio. Frost and freeze 
warnings were posted over Alabama, Georgia, the Carolinas and Tennessee. 
Flurries in Washington, D.C., failed to stop the National Cherry Blossom 
parade. Throngs of tourists and residents attended despite unseasonal cold and 
the absence of cherry blossoms, which last month bloomed early. But Seattle 
marked a 14th straight day without measurable rainfall -- a very unusual 
pattern. 
</P>
