<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAUDING LEHMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Re Robert Ward's April 1 review of Ian Hamilton's "Writers in Hollywood," I 
hasten to decline my share of a well-intentioned compliment. 
</P>
<P>
In my not-so-humble opinion, it was director Alexander Mackendrick who was the 
chief creative driving force behind the film "Sweet Smell of Success." It was 
his brilliance as director that gave the picture whatever qualities it has that 
have elicited praise over the years. And apparently neither author Hamilton nor 
reviewer Ward is aware that Mackendrick is the distinguished director of, among 
others, two British film classics: "Tight Little Island" and "The Man in the 
White Suit." 
</P>
<P>
ERNEST LEHMAN 
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
