<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: USDA PROVIDES DIFFERENT TECHNIQUES FOR CURING, DRYING, COOKING 
MEATS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR BUTCHER: Your recipe for beef jerky, which appeared at least a year ago 
and which I have made often, produces excellent jerky. However, at some point 
in my Food Guide readings, I came across a discussion of "safe cooking 
temperatures" and so called the United States Department of Agriculture to ask 
them about the slow drying at 150-degrees method. To my dismay, they did not 
recommend cooking any meat at lower than 325 and further to cook the meat to an 
internal temperature of 160. 
</P>
<P>
 -- A READER 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READER: Our government takes such very good care of us. If we listened to 
and adhered to all government recommendations, I'm quite sure that death would 
be optional, 160 degrees, indeed. I'll have my steak rare and 130 degrees, 
thank you. 
</P>
<P>
Next time you call the USDA, try to talk to a food scientist about curing and 
drying, not cooking. Curing and drying are two of the oldest methods of food 
preservation known to man, and they have served us well. Enjoy your jerky. 
</P>
<P>
For more good sound scientific information on the subject, I recommend: "A 
Complete Guide to Home Meat Curing" available from Morton Salt Co., P.O. Box 
355, Argo, Ill. 60501. The price is $1 plus 25 cents, shipping and handling. 
Also recommended: "How to Dry Foods" by Deanna DeLong (HP Books). 
</P>
<P>
 -- MERLE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR BUTCHER: This nutrition business certainly is out of hand and a pain in 
the neck. I am a retired old lady in my mid-'80s and terribly tired of hearing 
about cholesterol and what foods are good for you or terribly bad for you. 
</P>
<P>
I remember how in years long ago conversation at the dinner table with regard 
to food was about how good it looked and tasted and good recipes, etc. Those 
days are gone. 
</P>
<P>
 -- A READER 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READER: I hope not. The tide already shows signs of swinging back to some 
of the nutritional common sense of yesteryear. More and more these days I am 
hearing scientists and nutritionists, dietitians and such recommend pretty much 
the same thing Grandma used to: a well-balanced diet from the four basic food 
groups; a little moderation, and "get off your duff and go do the chores, the 
exercise will do you good." 
</P>
<P>
The whole cholesterol issue is being hotly debated in scientific circles these 
days and one would hope that out of all the debate will come some truth and 
perhaps even some common sense. In the meantime, be grateful that there is 
still some conversation around your dinner table. 
</P>
<P>
The latest for the younger set, for whom even fast food isn't fast enough, is 
the computerized ordering system now in place at several Arby's Roast Beef 
Shops. Just step right up to the computer and punch in your order. Faced with a 
barrage of complains about slow service, Arby's installed the system for 
customers who no longer have time to spend. 
</P>
<P>
 -- MERLE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR BUTCHER: When serving my family stuffed cabbage, the meat is always a 
bright pink. I suspect this is caused by some color additive in the ground 
meat. Am I right? 
</P>
<P>
 -- A READER 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READER: The cause of the pink color is nitrate, but it's not something 
added to the meat. Rather, it's the naturally occurring nitrate in the cabbage. 
Nitrate is added to meat products like ham and hot dogs and other sausage 
products to prevent botulism, which is why those products have a pink color. 
But green leaf vegetables also contain nitrates. According to Dr. George York, 
a good friend and one of the leading food scientists in the country, cabbage 
has 50 to 100 parts-per-million nitrates, more than most hot dogs and more than 
enough to turn the meat in a cabbage roll pink. If you would like an even 
pinker color, wrap your meat in spinach that contains 1,500 parts per million. 
</P>
<P>
 -- MERLE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR MERLE: Why do I see so much seafood, pork ribs, beef ribs, etc., market 
with bright tags saying "Thawed, Previously Frozen"? Why in heaven's name don't 
they leave them frozen, omit the thawing? 
</P>
<P>
 -- A READER 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READER: I don't know, but I suspect the reason markets thaw frozen meats 
is very likely because people won't buy them in the frozen state. And 
government regulations demand that we be told if the product has been frozen. 
If enough folks like you would ask for frozen seafood, pork and beef ribs, 
etc., you can bet markets would stop thawing them. 
</P>
<P>
 -- MERLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
